## What Your Employees Will Notice

- **No visible changes this week for most users.** The ACR Stealer campaign works by presenting convincing on-screen prompts that instruct users to take an action, such as copying and running a command; employees should be told that Microsoft and IT will never ask them to run commands from a pop-up or web page.
- **Windows 11 users may receive an update** that enables new encryption behavior in the background. No user action is required and no workflow changes result from this update.
- **Copilot users in GCC High and DoD environments** will find that Declarative Agents with Actions are now generally available, enabling Copilot to take actions in external systems and enterprise workflows directly from the chat interface.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog - ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Microsoft 365 Roadmap - Declarative Agents GCC High/DoD](https://www.microsoft.com/microsoft-365/roadmap?id=564606)*

---

## What Your Help Desk Should Expect

- **Increase in phishing and social-engineering reports** related to ClickFix-style lures. The ACR Stealer campaign uses browser pop-ups and web pages that instruct users to paste text into a command prompt. Help desk staff should be briefed to treat any such report as a potential active incident requiring escalation, not a routine password reset.
- **Questions about Windows updates** from users on Windows 11 24H2, 25H2, or 26H1 who notice KB5089573, KB5095091, or KB5095093 in their update history. These are legitimate, security-related updates and require no user-side action.
- **Exchange migration inquiries** may increase as IT teams accelerate planning ahead of the October ESU deadline; help desks supporting hybrid mail environments should expect questions about mail flow and calendar behavior during transition periods.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog - ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Exchange Team Blog - ESU End Date](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/reminder-exchange-2016-and-2019-esu-program-ends-in-october-2026/ba-p/4539033) · [Microsoft Security Community - Post-Quantum Windows](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-security-community/new-windows-features-to-secure-today-s-data-in-a-post-quantum/ba-p/4523370)*

