## If You Take No Action

**ACR Stealer credential-theft campaign:** Attackers are actively harvesting browser-stored credentials and authentication session tokens from enterprise environments right now. A stolen session token can grant an attacker access to email, files, and business applications without triggering a password or MFA prompt. The resulting breach would trigger notification obligations under HIPAA and most state privacy laws, expose the organization to cyber insurance claim scrutiny, and carry the reputational and legal costs of a confirmed data incident. Inaction here is not a deferred risk; the campaign is live.

**Exchange 2016/2019 end of patching support:** Any vulnerability discovered in Exchange 2016 or 2019 after October 2026 will remain permanently unpatched. On-premises email servers are among the most targeted entry points in enterprise breaches; an unpatched Exchange server directly undermines HIPAA, CMMC, and SOC 2 compliance postures and will likely render cyber insurance claims related to email-borne incidents ineligible for coverage. Organizations that do not complete migration before the deadline will be making a conscious choice to operate critical infrastructure with no security remediation path.

**Failure to apply July Exchange security updates:** Organizations running Exchange 2016 or 2019 that do not apply the July patches are operating with known, publicly disclosed vulnerabilities on their mail servers today. This is an immediate risk even before the October deadline, as attackers routinely weaponize published CVEs within days of disclosure.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog - ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Exchange Team Blog - ESU End Date](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/reminder-exchange-2016-and-2019-esu-program-ends-in-october-2026/ba-p/4539033) · [Exchange Team Blog - July Security Updates](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/released-july-2026-exchange-server-security-updates/ba-p/4534146)*